Sliding Window: Uses two pointers moving in the same direction to track a sub-segment of data.
Fast and Slow Pointers: Moves two pointers at different speeds to detect cycles or find midpoints.
Prefix Sum: Pre-calculates cumulative totals to allow instant range-sum lookups.
Binary Search: A two-pointer approach that halves the search space at every step.
Two Pointers (Multiple Arrays): One pointer per array used to merge or compare sorted datasets.
Divide and Conquer: Breaks a problem into two halves recursively (like Merge Sort).
Backtracking: Explores all possible paths and "backtracks" when a path fails.
Greedy Approach: Makes the best local choice at each step to find a global solution.
Dynamic Programming: Breaks problems into sub-problems and stores results to avoid re-calculation.
BFS (Breadth-First Search): Explores a graph or tree level by level using a queue.
DFS (Depth-First Search): Explores a graph or tree by going as deep as possible before backtracking.
Monotonic Stack: Uses a stack to keep elements in a specific order (increasing or decreasing).
